    <fr:title text="Ensuring well-formed horn clauses">Ensuring well-formed horn clauses</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Quiz</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Which of the following are well-formed horn clauses:
</html:p><html:ol><html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x < n) \to  q(x, n)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x, n) \land  (x < n) \to  \bot ]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x, y) \land  r(x) \to  p(x)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x, y) \to  p(x + 1, y)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x) \land  \neg  r(x) \to  p(x)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x) \lor  r(x) \to  p(x)]]></fr:tex></html:li>
  <html:li><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q(x) \to  x < n]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol><html:p>
  also: can the non-well-formed horn clauses be transformed into well-formed horn clauses?
</html:p>
  
    
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" expanded="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Solution</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:ol><html:li>
      Well-formed
    </html:li>
    <html:li>
      Well-formed
    </html:li>
    <html:li>
      Well-formed
    </html:li>
    <html:li>
      Not well-formed, has an expression in place of what is meant to be a <html:em>variable</html:em></html:li>
    <html:li>
      Not well-formed, as a reminder in disjunctive form a horn clause is 
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
        \neg  p \lor  \neg  q \lor  \neg  r \lor  \vdots  \lor  \neg  \phi  \lor  H
      ]]></fr:tex>
      we cannot have a negated query as it's disallowed by the syntax
    </html:li>
    <html:li>
      Not well-formed, see above, should be a conjunct in implication form
    </html:li>
    <html:li>
      Not well-formed, the head is a query (relation over a vector of <html:em>variables</html:em>) or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ol>
  <html:p>
    Yes, we can normalize the non-well-formed horn clauses for example through the introduction of fresh variables so as an example the clause
  </html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    q(x, y) \to  p(x + 1, y)
  ]]></fr:tex>
  <html:p>
    can be converted to:
  </html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
    q(x, y) \land  x' = x + 1 \to  p(x', y)
  ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
